main.java.de.bsi.tsesimulator.tse

Class TSEController

  • java.lang.Object
    • main.java.de.bsi.tsesimulator.tse.TSEController
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    SEAPI

    public class TSEController
extends java.lang.Object
implements SEAPI
    Represents the class that appears as a Technische Sicherheits Einrichtung (technical security application) to the outside world. It attempts to simulate such a TSE as defined in BSI TR-03153 and BSI-03151 and the additional technical guidelines mentioned there. This class implements most of the Secure Element API (SEAPI defined by TR-03151 and attempts to simulate the behavior of those functions as accurate as possible.
    This TSEController is the main class with which the user of the TSE-simulator should interact. Since the usage of this class may be rather complicated, it is necessary for the user to refer to the user guide of this simulator. That user guide describes in detail how the simulator can and should be configurated and used in own projects.

    Please be aware of the fact, that this program is only a simulator, not the one-and-only implementation of a TSE and should not be viewed as such.

    • Constructor Detail

      • TSEController

        public TSEController()
              throws LoadingFailedException
        Default constructor for the TSEController. The TSEController constructs a SecurityModule (SecurityModule) and a Storage. If the construction of the security module fails due to an IOException, this constructor throws a LoadingFailedException.
        Depending on whether persisted values are found under the directory path specified in config.properties this method behaves differently. If PersistentStorage.persistentValuesExist() returns true, the method attempts to read the values from the file and uses them to construct the SecurityModule and therefore the ERSSpecificModule and CryptoCore. This means that the clock and the signature counter of the CryptoCore are set to the stored values, as is the transaction counter in the ERSSpecificModule and the stati of the TSE and the SecurityModule.
        If no persistence file is found, everything is constructed with its default values. That means, "0" for the transaction number and the signature counter, "false" for seIsDisabled and "false" for tseIsInitialized.
        Throws:
        LoadingFailedException - if the constructor of the SecurityModule, Storage or PersistentStorage throws an IOException, and/or if reading the configuration file fails due to a missing path to the resource directory.
        Mitigation: Use PropertyValues.setPathToResourceDirectory(String) before constructing the TSEController.

      • TSEController

        public TSEController(java.lang.String pathToResourceDir)
              throws NoExternalConfigFilesException,
                     LoadingFailedException
        Constructor for the TSEController. Has to be given the path to the main configuration file, config.properties. The TSEController constructs a SecurityModule (SecurityModule) and a Storage. If the construction of the security module fails due to an IOException, this constructor throws a LoadingFailedException.
        Depending on whether persisted values are found under the directory path specified in config.properties this method behaves differently. If PersistentStorage.persistentValuesExist() returns true, the method attempts to read the values from the file and uses them to construct the SecurityModule and therefore the ERSSpecificModule and CryptoCore. This means that the clock and the signature counter of the CryptoCore are set to the stored values, as is the transaction counter in the ERSSpecificModule and the stati of the TSE and the SecurityModule.
        If no persistence file is found, everything is constructed with its default values. That means, "0" for the transaction number and the signature counter, "false" for seIsDisabled and "false" for tseIsInitialized. Depending on the configuration, this may also set the "description of the SE API".
        Parameters:
        pathToConfigFile - the (absolute) path pointing to the resource directory path pointing to config.properties.
        Throws:
        NoExternalConfigFilesException - if the path to the config.properties file is null,
        LoadingFailedException - if during the construction of the SecurityModule an IOException is thrown. if the constructor of the SecurityModule, Storage or PersistentStorage throws an IOException, and/or if reading the configuration file fails due to a missing path to the resource directory.
        Mitigation: Use PropertyValues.setPathToResourceDirectory(String) before constructing the TSEController.

        Used to register clients for the usage of the TSE. Only registered clients may use the TSE to document transactions. A logged in user with the role of "admin" is required to invoke the function successfully.
        Please note: keeping track of which clientIds are logged in and which are not is not performed by the TSE simulator.
        Parameters:
        clientId - the ID of the client to be added [INPUT PARAMETER, REQUIRED]
        Returns:
        if the execution of the function has been successful, the return value Constant.EXECUTION_OK SHALL be returned
        Throws:
        ErrorSecureElementDisabled - if the secure element of the TSE has been disabled
        ErrorSeApiNotInitialized - if the SeApi has not yet been initialized
        ErrorParameterMismatch - if the clientId is absent or not an ASN.1 PrintableString
        ErrorUserNotAuthenticated - if no user is logged in
        ErrorUserNotAuthorized - if a user is logged in but does not have the role of "admin"
        ClientIdAlreadyRegisteredException - if attempting to register a client that has already been registered before
        TooManyClientsException - if adding this client would result in a violation of maxNumberOfClients in config.properties and/or Constants#MAX_NUMBER_OF_CLIENTS

        public short deregisterClient(java.lang.String clientId)
                       throws ErrorSecureElementDisabled,
                              ErrorSeApiNotInitialized,
                              ErrorParameterMismatch,
                              ErrorUserNotAuthenticated,
                              ErrorUserNotAuthorized,
                              ClientIdNotRegisteredException
        Used to unregister clients from the TSE. Unregistered clients can no longer use the TSE to document their transactions. Clients may be re-registered using registerClient(String).
        Please note: keeping track of which clientIds are logged in and which are not is not performed by the TSE simulator. Therefore, the caller of this function might remove clients which still have open transactions. It is the responsibility of the caller to make sure, those transactions are terminated properly by using another client or re-registering the client that started them.
        Parameters:
        clientId - the ID of the client to be removed [INPUT PARAMETER, REQUIRED]
        Returns:

        Throws:

        ErrorSeApiNotInitialized - if the SeApi has not yet been initialized
        ErrorParameterMismatch - if the clientId is absent or not an ASN.1 PrintableString
        ErrorUserNotAuthenticated - if no user is logged in
        ErrorUserNotAuthorized - if a user is logged in but does not have the role of "admin"
        ClientIdNotRegisteredException - if attempting to remove a client that is currently not registered

      • gracefulShutdown

        public short gracefulShutdown()
                       throws GracefulShutdownFailedException,
                              PersistingFailedException
        Performs a graceful shutdown for the TSEController. This is useful, because one can not simply turn off the program in which the TSEController exists, rewrite some tests, and then use the TSEController (and therefore the simulator) as if nothing had happened. This method aims to help with that problem:
        It closes all remaining open transactions with a generic message indicating they were closed by a graceful shutdown,
        logs out any user that is still logged in,
        de-registers any clients still registered
        and persists all relevant data. Please note: using the simulator would now look like this: TSEController currentlyUsedController = new TSEController(); TEST currentlyUsedController.gracefulShutdown() currentlyUsedController = null; currentlyUsedController = new TSEController(); //this loads the persisted values!
        depending on number of open transactions, this may take a while!
        Returns:
        Constant.EXECUTION_OK if the execution went okay
        Throws:
        GracefulShutdownFailedException
        PersistingFailedException - if storing the important values of the simulator in PersistentStorage fails

        The function initialize starts the initialization of the SE API by the operator of the corresponding application. The initialization data in form of the description of the SE API is passed by the input parameter description. The description of the SE API MUST NOT have been set by the manufacturer.
        Specified by:
        initialize in interface SEAPI
        Parameters:
        description - short description of the SE API. The parameter SHALL only be used if the description of the SE API has not been set by the manufacturer [INPUT PARAMETER, REQUIRED]
        Returns:
        if the execution of the function has been successful, the return value EXECUTION_OK SHALL be returned
        Throws:
        ErrorSigningSystemOperationDataFailed - determination of the log message parts for the system operation data by the Secure Element failed
        ErrorStoringInitDataFailed - storing of the initialization data failed
        ErrorRetrieveLogMessageFailed - execution of the Secure Element functionality to retrieve log message parts has failed
        ErrorStorageFailure - storing of the log message has failed
        ErrorCertificateExpired - the certificate with the public key for the verification of the appropriate type of log messages is expired. Even if a certificate expired, the log message parts are created by the Secure Element and stored by the SE API. In this case, the exception ErrorCertificateExpired is raised only after the data of the log message has been stored.

        ErrorUserNotAuthenticated - the user who has invoked the function initialize has not the status authenticated
        ErrorDescriptionSetByManufacturer - the function initialize has been invoked with a value for the input parameter description although the description of the SE API has been set by the manufacturer
        ErrorSignatureCounterOverflow - the function initialize has been invoked although the value of the signature counter in the CryptoCore module has entered an illegal state

        logTime - represents the point in time of the Secure Element when the log message was created [OUTPUT PARAMETER, REQUIRED]
        serialNumber - represents hash value over the public key of the key pair that is used for the creation of signature values in transaction log messages [OUTPUT PARAMETER, REQUIRED]
        signatureCounter - represents the current value of the signature counter [OUTPUT PARAMETER, REQUIRED]
        signatureValue - represents the signature value [OUTPUT PARAMETER, OPTIONAL]
        Returns:
        if the execution of the function has been successful, the return value EXECUTION_OK SHALL be returned
        Throws:
        ErrorStartTransactionFailed - the execution of the Secure Element functionality to start a transaction failed
        ErrorRetrieveLogMessageFailed - the execution of the Secure Element functionality to retrieve log message parts has failed
        ErrorStorageFailure - storing of the log message failed
        ErrorSeApiNotInitialized - the SE API has not been initialized
        ErrorTimeNotSet - the managed data/time in the Secure Element has not been updated after the initialization of the SE API or a period of absence of current for the Secure Element
        ErrorCertificateExpired - the certificate with the public key for the verification of the appropriate type of log messages is expired. Even if a certificate expired, the log message parts are created by the Secure Element and stored by the SE API. In this case, the exception ErrorCertificateExpired is raised only after the data of the log message has been stored.
        ErrorSecureElementDisabled - the Secure Element has been disabled
        ErrorTransactionCounterOverflow - the function startTransaction has been invoked although the value of the transaction counter in the SecurityModule has entered an illegal state
        ErrorSignatureCounterOverflow - the function startTransaction has been invoked although the value of the signature counter in the CryptoCore module has entered an illegal state
